I'm not sure it would be possible to code ripostes so certain targets never get riposted, or if it's even wise.  It does add a lot of defensive power to our pets for everyday use, I'm surprised nobody has posted that thought.<P>We definately need pet immunity to fear at levels 59 and 60.  As it stands, magicians and necromancer pets can make a meaningful contribution to fights with monsters that AoE fear (ie Kunark dragons...), but beastlords can't.  Verant considered it unbalancing that magicians got this and not necromancers, so it was given to the necromancers (inherent ability of their spectre pet).  It is just as unbalancing for beastlords to be denied this as well.<P>I don't really care for the vapor idea.  It sounds neat, but you're basically asking for our pets to get Stonestance.  Spirit of Granite is basically just a glorified riposte with a guaranteed amount of damage to the riposte the pet does.  IMO, both of these ideas are overpowered.<P>Here's a simpler suggestion for alleviating the riposte damage on pets...implement two commands:  "/pet front" and "/pet rear".  One would tell your pet to attack from the front of the target, the other from behind.  We know the computer identifies front and back (riposte/parry cannot be performed on someone behind you, and backstabs cannot be performed from the front).  This would simply force the computer to strafe our pets around, remaining in front of or behind the target (and the computer already controls the pet's movement anyway).  This eliminates the possibility of riposte damage (or reduces, depending on how quickly the pet can strafe around to be on the other side).<P>This makes the 54 water and 53 skeleton pets significantly more viable (the backstabbing pets).<P>On second thought, this makes our pets basically immune to melee damage (except rampage).  Perhaps a command issued manually that forces our pets to switch sides only when we use it and not something the computer does automatically (such that we'd have to pay attention to our pets and the mob during combat, occasionally issuing the command).<P>--------------------<P>"Talk sense to a fool and he will call you foolish."   - Euripides
</FONT>
